Fiorucci Builds Design, Commercial Team Ahead of London Store Opening
¬†


 

Levi‚Äôs Chip Bergh Elected HP‚Äôs Independent Board Chairman
¬†




David Rosenblatt Named to Farfetch Group Board
¬†



Fiorucci Builds Design, Commercial Team Ahead of London Store Opening
Levi‚Äôs Chip Bergh Elected HP‚Äôs Independent Board Chairman
David Rosenblatt Named to Farfetch Group Board






Appeared In

Special Issue
Beauty Inc issue 11/11/2011






Forty floors above Fifth Avenue, in a tastefully decorated if somewhat bland room dominated by a Richard Serra lithograph, lies the corner office of John Demsey.

Group president of the EsteÃÅe Lauder Cos. Inc., Demsey oversees eight of the company‚Äôs key brands, including EsteÃÅe Lauder, MAC, Bobbi Brown, La Mer, Jo Malone, Tom Ford, Prescriptives and the recently acquired Smashbox. In all, industry sources estimate Demsey‚Äôs brands generated an estimated $5 billion of the $8.8 billion in net sales that the company reported for its fiscal year 2011.
This story first appeared in the November 11, 2011 issue of WWD.¬† Subscribe Today.
The 40th floor aerie is a visible manifestation of Demsey‚Äôs professional achievements, but the executive isn‚Äôt one to roost comfortably in an ivory tower. Rather, Demsey‚Äôs success stems from his prowess in knowing what‚Äôs happening outside the insular walls of his office. More than any other beauty executive working today, Demsey is a master at keeping his fingers on the pulse of pop culture, continually ahead of the curve in anticipating the next big thing ‚Äî be it in the worlds of fashion, music, art, celebrity, retail, photography, publishing or design. By applying that connectivity to the brands he oversees ‚Äî most notably starting with MAC  back in 1988 ‚Äî Demsey has helped redefine modern-day beauty branding.

¬†
‚ÄúThe brands that have long-term sustainability are the brands that live in the context of now ‚Äî not based on who you used to be,‚Äù says Demsey, who declined to comment on sales figures for this story.
¬†
Living in the context of now means that Demsey is as comfortable at Saks Fifth Avenue, schmoozing with its chief executive offiver Steve Sadove during a frenzied Fashion‚Äôs Night Out pit stop, as he is two hours later welcoming hipster songstress Beth Ditto in a makeshift dressing room at MAC‚Äôs SoHo store before she performs an electrifying set to adoring fans. It means navigating his way through throngs of cross-dressing fashionistas to greet Nicola Formichetti, Lady Gaga‚Äôs stylist turned fashion designer who tonight is opening a pop-up store in TriBeCa, and the next day escorting pop star Nicki Minaj to her front-row seat at Prabal Gurung amid the glare of flashbulbs.
¬†
‚ÄúIf anyone else looked at my schedule, they would think, Why on earth is he doing those things?‚Äù says Demsey. ‚ÄúYet what I know is that there is a rhyme and reason behind every single thing that I do.‚Äù
¬†
That approach is one of his most defining characteristics. ‚ÄúJohn‚Äôs greatest strength is his insight into the often not obvious aspects of the business, such as popular culture and distribution,‚Äù says Leonard Lauder, chairman emeritus of the EsteÃÅe Lauder Cos. Inc., who has known Demsey since 1991. ‚ÄúHe shows a tremendous flexibility in comprehending how each brand needs a unique approach. Each brand that he supervises has created its own unique personality and individual growth rate. No two brands look or soundalike. That‚Äôs beyond brilliant.‚Äù
¬†
Jane Hertzmark Hudis, the global brand president of EsteÃÅe Lauder, has seen firsthand how Demsey filters the myriad influences he surrounds himself with, parceling ideas to the brands they are most relevant for. ‚ÄúWhat he‚Äôs amazing at is that he has his finger on the pulse. He knows the beat, and he can go to the edge and exciting part of any opportunity,‚Äù she says. ‚ÄúHe has a sensibility about culture, about edge, about the next big trend, and it is percolating with him. He is sitting on it, thinking about it, and he looks among his brands for the right opportunity and puts it there. He has a sensibility to pick up whatever is about to happen and seize that and see where the next opportunity can be.‚Äù
Fabrizio Freda, the chief executive officer of Lauder under whose tenure has seen Demsey‚Äôs role at the company evolve from day-to-day brand steward to group strategic thinker, agrees. ‚ÄúJohn is strategic and creative at the same time,‚Äù says Freda. ‚ÄúHe is very good about taking a chance when he sees the opportunity, and enabling his team to have the courage to take a chance. He knows when the right moment is to take risk. He has a good hunter instinct.‚Äù
For proof, take the rejuvenation of the EsteÃÅe Lauder brand. Demsey was named its president in early 2005, after successfully transforming MAC from an indie makeup artist brand into a color cosmetics giant. While Lauder was undeniably a prestige sales powerhouse, its image had become staid and in need of modernizing. Demsey was very familiar with the brand ‚Äî his first job at the corporation was as its vice president of sales for the West Coast, and he diligently absorbed the teachings of EsteÃÅe Lauder and Leonard Lauder. However, it was the time he spent away from it that held the key to Demsey‚Äôs ideas for its reinvention. ‚ÄúThe great-est liberator to me was coming back after eight years at MAC, with fresh eyes,‚Äù he says. ‚ÄúThe ability to have fresh eyes is not forever, and I started thinking more abstractly in terms of what does EsteÃÅe Lauder really mean? Who is our competition? Who is really buying the product?
‚ÄúIf a brand is successful, there‚Äôs a reason, and the answer is usually sitting in the room,‚Äù he continues. ‚ÄúAnd I try to go back to the original DNA of what the brand was about.‚Äù
That thinking led Demsey to EsteÃÅe herself, who he saw in a new, more modern light. ‚ÄúI began to understand that she wasn‚Äôt conventional, that her command of point of sale, her point of view relative to product, the way she conceptualized things and the way she worked with Leonard were all quite different for the time.‚Äù And that thinking led Demsey to decide that it was time for a jolt. Enter Tom Ford, the superstar designer who had recently inked a deal with Lauder for an eponymous fragrance line and whose overtly sexual ethos was the polar opposite of Lauder‚Äôs genteel universe. Demsey decided to do a co-branded limited edition color cosmetics collection to be called the Tom Ford and EsteÃÅe Lauder Collection.
‚ÄúThe idea was a shock to the brand and a shock to the world,‚Äù he says. ‚ÄúIt was a short-term association for the EsteÃÅe Lauder brand, but it was a turning point in that it reframed the importance of aspiration, storytelling and establishing uniqueness and a point of difference to sell product.‚Äù

Aspiration is a word that comes up often in Demsey‚Äôs conversation. In his mind, it is the single most important attribute that the company sells. ‚ÄúBeauty in its abstract concept is an aspiration. It‚Äôs not always a reality,‚Äù he says. ‚ÄúThere is an aspirational element to beauty that exists from dollar stores all the way up to Bergdorf Goodman, because beauty in its ultimate is an aspiration.‚Äù
¬†
To that end, aspiration is the lens through which Demsey views all aspects of the business ‚Äî be it product development or distribution strategies, global expansion or brand messaging. The success of Tom Ford‚Äôs collaboration with EsteÃÅe Lauder helped clarify that vision even more. ‚ÄúAll of a sudden, I had people calling me for the brand who had never called before,‚Äù Demsey recalls. ‚ÄúThat started to stimulate the thought in terms of how do you define modern-day aspiration, where does it exist and how do you live it?‚Äù
The answer was China. Period. ‚ÄúThia Breen and I came to the conclusion that the aspirational future of the world was Asia, and that was really the pull in terms of where, if you wanted to win the hearts and minds of the aspirational consumer for the next 20, 30, 40 years, you‚Äôd better be successful there. To that end, Lauder shifted its message in China from ‚Äúless promotional to more aspirational,‚Äù Demsey says, with a clear emphasis on luxury skin care. The concept, Demsey points out, ‚Äúwas very similar to the way the brand was originally established in the U.S. in the late 1940s and ‚Äô50s at stores like Saks Fifth Avenue and I. Magnin.‚Äù

The strategy worked. Today, EsteÃÅe Lauder claims to be the number-one prestige beauty brand in its distribution and the fastest-growing Western brand in Asia. The EsteÃÅe Lauder Cos. doesn‚Äôt break out regional sales by brand, but sales in the Asia Pacific region increased 17 percent, or $250 million, for the fiscal year 2011, to almost $1.8 billion. Sales in China alone grew 33 percent, and the company expects it to become its largest market in Asia Pacific this year.
Still, it‚Äôs one thing to build a global business with a brand that already has more than $1 billion in sales. It‚Äôs quite another to do it with a brand from scratch, a feat Demsey is currently tackling with the introduction of an ambitious color cosmetics and skin care line under the Tom Ford banner. Although the 132-stockkeeping-unit line is currently bowing in just 45 doors worldwide, the launch is primarily a global play, not a U.S. one. ‚ÄúTom Ford has placed a big bet on China and Korea and, to a lesser extent, Japan,‚Äù says Demsey. ‚ÄúHe sees the future of luxury as heavily rooted in those capital cities in Asia.‚Äù
That being said, Tom Ford beauty won‚Äôt launch in Asia until sometime next year. While the brand currently has a strong fragrance and lipstick business with estimated global sales of $150 million at retail, and rich Chinese consumers have a predilection for luxury labels from the West, fragrance is still a cultural anomaly in Asia. ‚ÄúWe deliberately held off on the Asian articulation of the brand to make sure we understand everything that is working and to make sure it goes into the marketplace in the right way,‚Äù says Demsey.
The launch of Tom Ford is ambitious to be sure, but Demsey has proven himself to be an able brand builder over the years. When he took over MAC in 1998, it had an estimated wholesale volume of $140 million. Today, industry sources estimate its wholesale volume at more than $1.5 billion. The NPD Group reports the brand is ranked number one in prestige color, and is number one in the lip and eye categories, number two in foundation and number five in mascara. Those figures exclude sales in MAC‚Äôs own stores. Demsey declined to comment on the sales figure but does note that the MAC AIDS Fund raised about $3 million when he first arrived, a figure which has risen to $230 million collectively today ($38 at million of that in the last fiscal year alone).
¬†
Although sources estimate Tom Ford‚Äôs makeup and skin care is expected to hit $40 million in first-year sales ‚Äî a pittance compared to Lauder‚Äôs billion-dollar behemoths ‚Äî the company has thrown the full weight of its support behind it. ‚ÄúNew brands today are the big brands of tomorrow,‚Äù says William Lauder, chairman of the EsteÃÅe Lauder Cos. ‚ÄúI remember being asked to speak once about MAC and niche brands at a conference, and my comment was, ‚ÄòEvery brand has a niche. Some are bigger than others. The characterization of MAC as niche still holds today ‚Äî it just has a very nice niche.‚Äù
Demsey is modest about the brand‚Äôs success. ‚ÄúWhen I first got to MAC, Leonard Lauder told me to make it more MAC than it ever was. I thought, ‚ÄòWhatever that means,‚Äô‚Äù he laughingly remembers.

Demsey has a droll manner when speaking, and he tends to think as others write ‚Äî in fully formed paragraphs that segue crisply from one thought to the next, each point building upon theprevious to substantiate the original hypothesis. It‚Äôs a mana- gerial style under which people either thrive or wilt, associ- ates say. Many of his key team members have been with him for 10-plus years, and laud his leadership technique. Still, for others, his flashes of steeliness can be off-putting.
Says James Gager, who today is senior vice president and group creative director of the MAC, La Mer and Jo Malone brands, and who was one of the first people Demsey tapped for MAC, ‚ÄúI‚Äôm not for everybody as a person. I‚Äôm a very specific guy. What I admire about John is that he truly understands what I bring to the party. And I could say that about John, as well. He‚Äôs not for everybody either, but he brings special skills to whatever situation he is in, and that‚Äôs important in terms of being a success and a leader.‚Äù
He‚Äôs also not afraid to take risks. Jennifer Balbier, senior vice president of global product development for artistry brands, remembers the birth of MAC‚Äôs Mineralize line. ‚ÄúI found a complex in our lab comprised of 77 minerals fermented in yeast water, and a little factory in Italy ‚Äî who we didn‚Äôt do business with ‚Äî who could bake it,‚Äù she recounts. ‚ÄúBare Escentuals was starting to explode, but I was having a hard time getting anybody interested. I took it to John, who believed in my vision and said, ‚ÄòLet‚Äôs do it.‚Äô‚Äù The risk paid off. Today, Mineralize is one of MAC‚Äôs biggest franchises.
As Demsey delved deeper into MAC, he began to fulfill Leonard Lauder‚Äôs mandate. ‚ÄúI came to understand what he meant, that the life force of the brand was its counterculture beginnings and the focus on the makeup artist and the theatricality, and that the heart and soul was the MAC AIDS Fund,‚Äù he says. Demsey eschewed traditional beauty-industry brand-building strategies (such as print advertising) and focused instead on building a passionate community of acolytes, using the credo, all ages, all races, all sexes. ‚ÄúWe built the brand on word of mouth and on a community social relevance platform that was in a fashion context,‚Äù he says.
Though this was the pre-Facebook age, the brand was able to effectively harness the rise of social media because it already had such a loyal community, particularly among makeup artists. ‚ÄúThe fashion outreach, the events, the pop-culture icons ‚Äî those were the underpinnings of MAC,‚Äù Demsey says. ‚ÄúAdd into that when the Internet and community and blogs became a driving force for how you communicate brand, and suddenly you have a brand that didn‚Äôt advertise except for Viva Glam becoming the most active brand in the online community, because it was authentically sitting in the middle of the content. For MAC, that was another game-changer, not by design, but because it was authentic and organically there.‚Äù
¬†
MAC became synonymous with fashion ‚Äî it was the original and is still one of the most involved beauty sponsors of fashion week, both in New York and worldwide ‚Äî as well as pop culture. Demsey tapped everyone from Lil Kim to Lady Gaga to star as the faces of Viva Glam, the MAC lipstick whose proceeds are completely funneled to charity, demonstrating an ability to recognize star potential that rivals that of a teenager.
¬†
‚ÄúJohn is tapped in not just because he‚Äôs a marketer but because he‚Äôs a consumer,‚Äù says Sarah Brown, Vogue‚Äôs beauty director. ‚ÄúWhen he signed Nicki Minaj, I was only vaguely aware of her, and he said, ‚ÄòNo, she‚Äôs going to be big.‚Äô Look at her now, a year later,‚Äù Brown says of the budding superstar. ‚ÄúThe same thing with Lady Gaga,‚Äù she continues. ‚ÄúHe has incredible instincts for what is going to explode and sell. Here‚Äôs this guy in a beautifully tailored suit who looks like a businessman, and is a businessman, but he‚Äôs also a voracious consumer of pop culture.‚Äù
(When asked what he spotted in Minaj that wasn‚Äôt immediately apparent to others, Demsey turns unchar- acteristically reticent ‚Äî ‚ÄúMy niece is a fan of Lil‚Äô Wayne. She enlightened me‚Äù ‚Äî and he likewise refuses to name names when asked for potential phenoms on the rise.)
The amount of media that Demsey digests is astonishing in its scope. ‚ÄúI watch a lot of TV. I go to a lot of theater. When I‚Äôm home late at night and reading and on my computer, I multitask. I watch Morning Joe, CNN, MSNBC, CNBC, the Today show. I like watching talk shows, like Oprah or Ellen or Kelly and Regis. I like reality TV and the Housewives,‚Äù Demsey ticks off. ‚ÄúI get all of the top celebrity magazines for the U.S., the U.K., France. I get Spanish and Italian Vanity Fair. I like to read Point de Vue to see what the royalist European point of view is. I surf YouTube, and I always look at Billboard to see what the top songs are in each country. If you look at fashion, at celebrity, at music, that tells you a lot about where people‚Äôs minds are.‚Äù
Demsey pauses to take a breath. ‚ÄúWhen I travel, I want to know what‚Äôs going on, so I go a day in advance,‚Äù he continues. ‚ÄúI ask the office to have in my room a stack of 40 or 50 magazines, from lifestyle to fashion to celebrity, and I‚Äôll turn on MTV, no matter what the language is. I always go to the hot neighborhood, just to sit and see what people look like. I‚Äôm also addicted to going on The Sartorialist. You learn a lot ‚Äî street culture and pop culture infuse themselves into what‚Äôs commercial.‚Äù

Demsey is continually filtering the new developments he picks up around the world, and has successfully applied many of those lessons to MAC. ‚ÄúIf you look at MAC, most of the successes we have around the world, there is generally a flagship store that we own, which is not a beauty concept, it‚Äôs a fashion concept,‚Äù he says. ‚ÄúThe decision to make MAC into a retailer was a defining tenet that to this day matters for the brand.‚Äù
¬†
Demsey actually began his career in retail, clocking time at Bloomingdale‚Äôs, Macy‚Äôs and Saks before joining the brand side. He points to recent phenomenons such as pop-up stores, flash sales, underground stores and crowdsourcing as factors that are changing the way he approaches the sector. ‚ÄúRetailing is becoming interesting,‚Äù he says. ‚ÄúPeople want to go to new environments and discover new things. People don‚Äôt just want to be sold product. They want brand experiences. They want feelings. They want to have a good time.‚ÄúThe forms of commerce and communication and luxury and prestige and aspiration are starting to blur,‚Äù he continues. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs incredibly exciting and incredibly tricky. It‚Äôs a very fine line between what‚Äôs prestige, what‚Äôs masstige, what‚Äôs mass and how they cross over.‚Äù Out of the blurring must come extreme focus. ‚ÄúIn the midst of all this clutter,‚Äù he maintains, ‚Äúyou must go back to the brand story. A long-term business isn‚Äôt sustainable unless you‚Äôve got a strong brand story and can keep telling it in new ways and keep it fresh over and over and over again.‚Äù
Like his sister brand Clinique, Demsey has successfully tapped into the power of national television advertising to tell the EsteÃÅe Lauder story. (‚ÄúIf you would have told me four years ago that the big news in marketing cosmetics was broadcast, I would have been surprised,‚Äù he deadpans.)
Another fundamental change he grapples with balancing is the incredible fragmentation of media. ‚ÄúYou used to be defined by whether you advertised or didn‚Äôt advertise, or whether you were a word-of-mouth brand or not, or if you were on a paid for media basis or an earned media basis,‚Äù he says. ‚ÄúWhat community, online and YouTube have done is level the playing field. Just having a lot of money doesn‚Äôt mean you‚Äôre going to win the communications game. Strategic media tactics ‚Äî in terms of breaking through the clutter ‚Äî and ideas and brand stories matter a lot.‚Äù
One such brand story is Smashbox Beauty Cosmetics, the Hollywood-based makeup brand the EsteÃÅe Lauder Cos. acquired in May 2010 for a reported $200 million to $300 million. Demsey had long known its founders, Dean and Davis Factor, the great-grandsons of makeup legend Max Factor, and helped spearhead the acquisition. ‚ÄúI thought Smashbox had a unique opportunity to institutionalize the Hollywood makeup position, which has been lost,‚Äù he says. ‚ÄúI also liked that they‚Äôre in the distribution that most of my brands are not. I know that people who buy my brands also shop in those channels,‚Äù he continues, referring to Smashbox‚Äôs primary outlets, such as QVC, Sephora and Ulta. ‚ÄúThe development of Smashbox and the changing distribution patterns in terms of what you consider prestige to be, or multispecialty retailing, is an important evolutionary step in terms of the EsteÃÅe Lauder Companies‚Äô approach to an important segment of the market.‚Äù
Demsey also sees huge potential for Smashbox in Asia, where it is virtually non-existent. ‚ÄúIn the time we were associated with Stila, the one part of the world where it was very successful was Japan and Hong Kong and Taiwan, and that was not a Hollywood position the way that this is,‚Äù he says, ‚Äúso I know that a Hollywood position done correctly is commercial.‚Äù
¬†
Above providing the potential for another brand-turnaround success story, Smashbox ‚Äî which also encompasses a photo studio and for which celebrity pho- tographer Davis Factor continues to be a creative force ‚Äî most of all epitomizes the personal and professional passions that drive Demsey. An ardent photography enthusiast whose extensive collection lines the walls of his Upper East Side town house, Demsey is driven by the coupling of the creative with the business. (To wit: In one swoop, he recently bought four pictures during a day of management meetings.) ‚ÄúFred Langhammer [Lauder‚Äôs chief executive officer from 1999‚Äì2004] used to say that nothing good comes without growth,‚Äù Demsey muses. ‚ÄúThis is not just an exercise in branding. It‚Äôs the convergence of business dynamics, creativity, intuition, marketing and brand development. The reason why I love my job so much is the left-brain, right-brain thing,‚Äù he continues. ‚ÄúTo be successful today, you have to be able to do both.‚Äù
The Demsey Doctrine: 5 Key Points
I Want My MTV: Popular culture drives mass consumption. Being plugged in‚Äî to movies, music, art, style, celebrity‚Äîis crucial.
Shock and Awe: Big ideas (like Tom Ford for EsteÃÅe Lauder) can make an instant difference in a business where perception and reality are closely aligned.
Beauty Is Aspiration. Period: Demsey‚Äôs not selling lipstick. He‚Äôs selling the universal desire to be beautiful that exists across all price points, all retail channels and all geographies.
Fun and Games: Women shop because they like to have new experiences‚Äînot because they need a new product. Retail must deliver a memorable moment.
The Level Playing Field: In a world of fragmented media, all brands are equal.
¬†




